              "passage_text": "Brazilian regulation requires companies to establish and enforce blackout periods (períodos de vedação à negociação). Under CVM Resolution 44/2021:\n\n- A mandatory blackout applies for the 15-day period immediately preceding the disclosure of quarterly (ITR) and annual (DFP) financial results.\n- Companies must establish their own \"securities trading policy\" (política de negociação de valores mobiliários) defining blackout periods, pre-clearance procedures, and permitted transactions (e.g., 10b5-1 equivalent plans for pre-scheduled diversification programs, called \"programas de negociação\" in Brazil).\n- Additional blackout periods apply whenever a Material Fact has been decided upon internally but not yet disclosed (the \"silent period\" before a deal announcement).\n\nLarge Brazilian companies (Petrobras, Vale, Itaú) have comprehensive securities trading policies that establish rolling blackouts aligned with the earnings calendar and additional windows for deal-specific restrictions.\n\n---",
