              "passage_text": "### The Fundamental Economic Distinction\n\nA conventional FII (often called a FII tijolo, or brick-and-mortar FII) owns completed, income-generating properties. Its return comes from two sources: rental income distributed monthly to quotaholders, and appreciation in property values over time. The cash flow profile is relatively stable and predictable, anchored to lease contracts with defined durations and adjustment clauses.\n\nA development FII, by contrast, finances the creation of new properties. Its capital is deployed into projects that do not yet exist — or exist only partially — and returns are generated when the completed project is sold, either unit by unit to end buyers or in bulk to institutional investors. The return profile is lumpy, back-loaded, and subject to execution risk.\n\n### Income Distribution Dynamics\n\nConventional FIIs are attractive to income investors in part because CVM regulations require FIIs to distribute at least 95% of their accounting earnings semi-annually (in practice, most distribute monthly). Development FIIs, which generate income primarily upon project completion and sale, face a mismatch: their investment horizon is typically 3-6 years for each project, during which there may be limited or no distributable income.\n\nSome development FIIs manage this by structuring a portion of their portfolio in income-generating assets to provide ongoing distributions while the development projects mature. Pure development FIIs may go extended periods without distributions, relying instead on eventual capital gain recognition upon sale of completed units or projects.\n\n---",
