          "answer": "For a Brazilian investor with only BRL liabilities, Decade’s convictions frame IVVB11-style dollar exposure as an optional strategic diversifier rather than a strict liability-matching necessity. The hedge “necessity” case is strongest when the investor has foreign-currency obligations; for fully local portfolios, the rationale shifts to portfolio diversification, because the dollar can appreciate in global risk-off episodes when Brazilian assets tend to fall, and Decade cites 5–15% FX exposure as potentially reducing total portfolio volatility for local investors with 100% BRL assets.[1]\n\nIVVB11 is not a pure currency hedge: it combines USD/BRL exposure with the underlying S&P 500 equity risk. Decade explicitly distinguishes dollarized ETFs from pure FX funds on that basis, and says IVVB11-type ETFs are generally superior for investors seeking dollar exposure plus returns from real assets, while pure FX funds make more sense only when the objective is exclusively currency hedging.[2]\n\nDecade’s ETF portfolio framework treats IVVB11 as a meaningful portfolio building block, not merely a tactical afterthought: a simple core portfolio for a Brazilian investor “could include” 20–30% in IVVB11 for dollarization and U.S. market exposure, while also emphasizing that the strategic asset allocation decision comes before ETF selection.[3]\n\nBottom line: with only BRL liabilities, dollar exposure via IVVB11 is not presented as mandatory hedge coverage; it is presented as a legitimate, often efficient, long-term diversification sleeve—potentially structural, but sized according to the investor’s strategic allocation rather than required by liabilities.[1][2][3]",
