              "passage_id": "macroeconomic_factors_brazilian_markets#9-china-dependency-risk-china-dependency",
              "document": "Macroeconomic Factors Affecting Brazilian Financial Markets",
              "heading": "9. China Dependency Risk {#china-dependency}",
              "heading_path": [
                "Macroeconomic Factors Affecting Brazilian Financial Markets",
                "9. China Dependency Risk {#china-dependency}"
              ],
              "passage_text": "### Quantifying the Exposure\n\nChina is Brazil's largest trading partner by a significant margin. The China dependency can be quantified:\n\n- ~25–30% of total Brazilian exports flow to China\n- ~22% of total imports originate from China (manufactured goods, electronics, machinery)\n- Brazil runs a trade surplus with China driven entirely by commodities; manufactured goods trade is in deficit\n\n**Sector-specific China dependencies:**\n\n| Sector | China Exposure | Primary Risk |\n|---|---|---|\n| Iron ore (Vale) | ~80% of exports | Chinese real estate/steel demand |\n| Soybeans | ~70% of exports | Chinese pork cycle, feed demand |\n| Beef | ~30% of exports | Chinese food safety policy |\n| Cellulose/Pulp | ~40% of exports | Chinese packaging demand |\n| Crude Oil | ~30% of exports | Chinese refinery utilization |\n\n### Transmission Channels of a China Slowdown\n\n**1. Commodity Price Channel (most direct)**\nA 10% decline in Chinese steel production has historically caused a 15–25% decline in iron ore prices. A decline in Chinese soy imports of 5% impacts Chicago and Brazilian soy prices by 5–10%.\n\n**2. BRL Channel**\nAs commodity prices fall, Brazilian export receipts decline, the current account weakens, and BRL depreciates. This is partially self-correcting (BRL weakness restores export competitiveness in some sectors) but exacerbates inflation.\n\n**3. Corporate Earnings Channel**\nVale's earnings are the most direct exposure. Petrobras has lower direct China exposure (oil is globally priced), but indirect exposure through global risk sentiment.\n\n**4. Sovereign Risk Channel**\nIf China's slowdown is severe enough to trigger a global recession, Brazil's fiscal position deteriorates as tax revenues decline (particularly from commodity-linked taxes) and the BCB may be constrained in cutting rates due to BRL depreciation and inflation passthrough.\n\n### China Risk as a Portfolio Construction Input\n\nGiven this dependency, Brazilian equity portfolios should stress-test their China exposure. A portfolio heavy in Vale, CSNA (steel), and agri-related names is implicitly long Chinese growth. Advisors should ensure clients understand that \"Brazilian equity exposure\" is often partially \"Chinese growth exposure via commodity prices.\"\n\n---",
